    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start for the intro. Some of my students might ask if there are other ways to look at \"due process\" though, like if it's just about the legal procedures and the steps the government has to follow. Should I include that in the lesson, or is substantive due process really the main thing that matters for constitutional rights?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You should absolutely include the distinction between procedural and substantive due process, but frame it as a debate rather than a settled fact. Procedural due process is merely the \"how\" of government action, while substantive due process is the \"what\" that actually protects your students' civil rights. Ignoring the procedural side would give a misleading picture of how the Constitution works, but emphasizing substantive due process is crucial for understanding how the 14th Amendment has been used to expand liberty.",
      "source": "target",
